There are several theories about where the first case might have originated (the so-called zero patient).
The first case that was known of the new coronavirus can be traced back to December 1, 2019 in Wuhan, Hubei, China.
Over the course of a month, the number of cases of coronavirus in Hubei gradually increased.
These were mainly linked to Huanan's wholesale seafood market, which also sold live animals, and one theory is that the virus originates from one of these animals; or, in other words, it has a zoonotic origin. On 26 December, a number of cases of unknown cause pneumonia were observed of which Dr. Zhang Jixian was in charge at Hubei Provincial Hospital, who reported to Jianghan CDC in Wuhan on 27 December.
On December 30, a group of doctors at Wuhan Central Hospital warned their colleagues about a "coronavirus similar to SARS".
